      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Accents on the Wrong Syl-LA-ble'' (Itineraries, Business Day, June 5):</p>
        <p>Bravo to Jennifer Pawlitschek, the accent coach from your article, for her statement that the term accent reduction ''is learning an American accent.''</p>
        <p>In my linguistics courses, I always ask students if they think they speak with an accent. The foreign born and those from the South always raise their hands, and sometimes those who think they sound ''Long Gilandy.''</p>
        <p>Of course, the right answer is that we all have accents. Some are just more noticed and judged than others.</p>
        <p>Susan J. Behrens  Brooklyn, June 5, 2007</p>
        <p>The writer is an associate professor of communication sciences and disorders at Marymount Manhattan College.</p>
      </block>
